Adult/immature.description: Juniper and Oak Titmice look extremely similar, but generally do not overlap except in extreme northern California. Juniper Titmice average slightly grayer, and their calls are different.
Gray Vireos have a heavier bill than Oak Titmice and they lack the Oak Titmouse's crest. They also have pale spectacles, a feature that Oak Titmice don't have.
Plumbeous Vireos have heavier bills and show more contrast than Oak Titmice, with pale spectacles and white wingbars, 2 features that Oak Titmice don't have.

Male (Pacific).description: Bushtits are smaller and thinner, with even shorter, stubbier bills and more frenetic actions than Oak Titmice. They also lack the Oak Titmouse's crest.

Adult.description: The range of Tufted Titmice does not overlap with Oak Titmouse. Tufted Titmouse are darker gray with a cinnamon wash on the sides that Oak Titmice lack.
